description.p:
allows the player to learn fingering techniques without the need for an on-site individual instructor;


allows the player to play the instrument in a natural position;


allows a high degree of interaction between an instructor and a student at different locations;


allows significant control over all facets of the instruction process;


can be incorporated into an instrument in a manner that allows the instrument to played normally when not used as an instructional instrument; and


can be easily and inexpensively manufactured using currently available technologies.

FIG. 1 is a plan, elevational view depicting an instructional guitar of the present invention and schematically depicting certain components thereof;


FIGS. 2A and 2B are sectional views taken along lines 2--2 in FIG. 1;


FIG. 3 is a top plan view of a portion of the guitar depicted in FIG. 2A showing an instructional grid forming a part thereof;


FIG. 4 is a simplified block diagram depicting an exemplary electrical portion that may be used with the instructional guitar of FIG. 1.
